ive force external to the self but something that was tied to acting in time. Divided only by walls and doors, waiters sought out occasions to improve their lot. At other times, they disrupted the scripts accorded them. Situated at the intersection of history, literature, and the history of art and architecture, this wide-ranging study demonstrates that waiting has a history that has much to tell us about social and power relations in the past and present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEntrance halls in literature. 0aEuropean literaturexThemes, motives. 0aSpace in literature. 0aTime in literature. 0aWaiting (Philosophy) in literature. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  ahistory of time.  apremodern Europe.  asocial hierarchy.  atemporality.  awaiting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363703040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637030423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637030/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles